vigate the competitive landscape effectively. [Data: Concepts (1, 2); Relationships (10, 11)]\"\n        }},\n        {{\n            \"summary\": \"Explain and apply sensitivity analysis to decision-making problems\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Sensitivity analysis calculates how responsive a decision is to changes in any of the variables used in making that decision. It looks at one variable at a time and measures how much the variable can change by (in percentage terms) before affecting the decision. The smaller the percentage, the more sensitive the decision is to that variable. Sensitivity % = Profit/Variable  [Data: Concepts (3)]\"\n        }}\n    ]\n}}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\n611,\"\"\"LINEAR PROGRAMMING\"\"\",\"\"\"Linear programming is a mathematical method used to determine the best possible outcome or solution from a given set of parameters or list of requirements, which are linear in nature. It involves formulating an objective function to either maximize contribution or minimize cost, and expressing constraints as linear equations. Linear programming is particularly useful for problems involving the rationing of scarce resources between products to achieve optimum benefit. The optimal solution can be identified graphically or solved algebraically using simultaneous equations.\"\"\",12\n613,\"\"\"CONSTRAINTS\"\"\",\"Constraints are the limitations or requirements that must be satisfied in an optimization problem. They define the boundaries of the feasible region. In linear programming, constraints are limitations or restrictions on the decision variables, which can include resource constraints, production constraints, and levels of demand, and are typically expressed in terms of inequalities. Examples of constraints include:\n\n1. Material constraints: \\(3x + y \\leq 4,200\\)\n2. Labour constraints: \\(4x + 0.5y \\leq 3,000\\)\n3. Non-negativity constraints: \\(b \\geq 0\\)\n4. Restriction on A: \\(a \\geq 1,000\\)\n5. Materials constraints: \\(3a + 4b \\leq 30,000\\)\n6. Labour constraints: \\(5a + 3b \\leq 36,000\\)\n\nThese constraints ensure that the solutions to the optimization problem remain within the feasible region defined by these boundaries.\",5\n618,\"\"\"OBJECTIVE FUNCTION METHOD\"\"\",\"The objective function method involves determining how contribution varies with product output. It uses iso-contribution lines to show all combinations of variables that produce a specific value of contribution. This method helps identify the optimal production mix that maximizes contribution within given constraints. Additionally, the objective function method involves evaluating the objective function at each vertex of the feasible region to determine which vertex yields the optimal solution.\",5\n616,\"\"\"FEASIBLE REGION\"\"\",\"In linear programming, the \"\"FEASIBLE REGION\"\" is the set of all possible points that satisfy all constraints. It is typically represented as a polygonal area on a graph where the optimal solution lies. Specifically, the feasible region is the area on a graph that satisfies all the constraints of the model. For example, in the context of Cut and Stitch, it is the region OABCD on the graph where the constraints for tailors' time, fabric, and production limits intersect. This region represents all possible values for the variables that meet the given constraints and is where the optimal solution for maximizing contribution can be found.\",9\n1681,\"\"\"LINEAR PROGRAMMING MODEL FOR CUT AND STITCH\"\"\",\"\"\"The linear programming model for Cut and Stitch includes variables for the number of work suits (W) and lounge suits (L) produced, an objective function to maximize contribution (C = 48W + 40L), and constraints related to tailors' time (7W + 5L \u2264 3,500 hours), fabric (2W + 2L \u2264 1,200 meters), and production limits for work suits (W \u2264 400). The feasible region and optimal point are identified on a graph.\"\"\",7\n1707,\"\"\"PRODUCTION CONSTRAINTS FOR PRODUCT F AND D\"\"\",\"\"\"The production constraints for Product F and D are given by the formulas: Materials: 4F + 6D = 2500, Labour: 10F + 8D = 4000, Machine time: 5F + 10D = 3200, Demand for D: 250.\"\"\",4\n614,\"\"\"GRAPHING A LINEAR PROGRAMMING MODEL\"\"\",\"\"\"The process of graphing a linear programming model includes defining unknowns, formulating the objective function, expressing constraints as inequalities, and plotting all constraints on a graph to identify the feasible region. The optimal solution can be solved using the objective function method or the simultaneous equation method.\"\"\",3\n612,\"\"\"OBJECTIVE FUNCTION\"\"\",\"The objective function in linear programming is a mathematical expression that defines the goal of the optimization, such as maximizing profit or minimizing cost. It quantifies the objective of a linear programming problem and is based on the assumption that both the objective and the constraints can be expressed as linear equations. In this context, there are two specific instances of objective functions provided: one is \\(15x + 12y\\), and another is \\(9a + 23b\\), where 'a' and 'b' represent the number of units of products A and B to be produced, respectively.\",3\n617,\"\"\"SIMULTANEOUS EQUATIONS METHOD\"\"\",The Simultaneous Equations Method is an algebraic approach used in linear programming to find the optimal solution by solving the system of linear equations formed by the constraints. This method is utilized to identify the point of maximum contribution by calculating the contribution at each possible maximum point of intersection within the feasible region.,3\n620,\"\"\"PRODUCTION CONSTRAINTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Production constraints\"\" refer to limitations on the production capacity or capabilities in a linear programming problem. These constraints are typically expressed as linear inequalities. Specifically, the production constraints include:\n\n- Build time: \\(24x + 20y \\leq 1,800,000\\)\n- Program time: \\(16x + 14y \\leq 1,680,000\\)\n- Test time: \\(10x + 4y \\leq 720,000\\)\n\nAdditionally, there are non-negativity constraints, which require that \\(x\\) and \\(y\\) be greater than or equal to 0. There are also sales constraints, which limit \\(x\\) to a maximum of 85,000 units and \\(y\\) to a maximum of 66,000 units.\",3\n2140,\"\"\"CONTRIBUTION FUNCTION\"\"\",\"\"\"Contribution function: C = 30x + 40y, where x is the number of units of Xeno to be produced and y is the number of units of Yong to be produced.\"\"\",2\n615,\"\"\"EXAMPLE OF LINEAR PROGRAMMING\"\"\",\"\"\"A company makes two products, cabinets and chests, which pass through carpentry and polishing departments. The time spent in each department and the available hours are given. The contribution to profit and fixed overheads is $100 for a cabinet and $150 for a chest. The optimal product mix to maximize total contribution to profit is calculated using linear programming.\"\"\",2\n622,\"\"\"ISO-CONTRIBUTION LINES\"\"\",\"\"\"Iso-contribution lines are lines on a graph where every point on each line gives the same contribution value. These lines are parallel to each other and help in identifying the optimal solution for maximizing contribution.\"\"\",5\n623,\"\"\"OPTIMAL SOLUTION\"\"\",\"\"\"The optimal solution is the combination of production quantities that maximizes the contribution within the feasible region. It is found at the point where the highest iso-contribution line intersects the boundary of the feasible region.\"\"\",4\n625,\"\"\"GRAPHICAL METHOD FOR OPTIMIZATION\"\"\",\"\"\"The graphical method for optimization involves plotting constraints on a graph, identifying the feasible region, and using iso-contribution lines to find the optimal solution that maximizes contribution.\"\"\",4\n1711,\"\"\"OPTIMUM PRODUCTION PLAN FOR LARGE APPLIANCES DIVISION\"\"\",\"\"\"The optimum production plan for the Large Appliances division is 240 units of Product F and 200 units of Product D, calculated using linear programming.\"\"\",1\n1712,\"\"\"QUIZ ON LINEAR PROGRAMMING AND LIMITING FACTORS\"\"\",\"\"\"This quiz involves questions on linear programming and limiting factors, including calculating contribution per unit of limiting factor, total contribution using simultaneous equations, and understanding shadow prices and slack values.\"\"\",1\n2139,\"\"\"OPTIMAL PRODUCTION STRATEGY FOR TABLET CO USING LINEAR PROGRAMMING\"\"\",\"\"\"Tablet Co makes two types of tablet computers, the Xeno (X) and the Yong (Y). The company uses linear programming to determine the optimal production plan to maximize contribution, considering constraints in build, program, and test stages.\"\"\",1\n1682,\"\"\"OPTIMAL POINT\"\"\",\"\"\"The optimal point in a linear programming model is the point within the feasible region that maximizes or minimizes the objective function. For Cut and Stitch, point B is the optimal point where contribution is maximized.\"\"\",3\n1683,\"\"\"GRAPHICAL METHOD FOR LINEAR PROGRAMMING\"\"\",\"\"\"The graphical method for solving linear programming problems involves plotting the constraints on a graph, identifying the feasible region, and finding the optimal point where the objective function is maximized or minimized. It is typically used for problems with two variables.\"\"\",3\n624,\"\"\"CONTRIBUTION LINE\"\"\",\"A contribution line in a linear programming graph represents the value of the objective function, such as contribution or profit, at different points. For Cut and Stitch, a sample contribution line passes through the point where W = 200 and L = 0, with a contribution value of $9,600. This line shows all combinations of variables that produce a specific value of contribution and is used to identify the optimal solution for maximizing contribution. The slope of the contribution line helps in identifying the point of maximum contribution within the feasible region, representing the total contribution for different combinations of products.\",3\n1684,\"\"\"WORK SUITS\"\"\",\"\"\"Work suits are one of the two types of suits produced by Cut and Stitch, with a production limit of 400 units and a contribution of $48 per unit.\"\"\",1\n1685,\"\"\"LOUNGE SUITS\"\"\",\"\"\"Lounge suits are one of the two types of suits produced by Cut and Stitch, with no specific production limit mentioned and a contribution of $40 per unit.\"\"\",1\n619,\"\"\"RESOURCE CONSTRAINTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Resource constraints are limitations on the availability of resources such as time, materials, and labor in a linear programming problem. They are expressed as linear inequalities.\"\"\",1\n621,\"\"\"LEVELS OF DEMAND\"\"\",\"\"\"Levels of demand refer to the required quantities of products or services that must be met in a linear programming problem. They are expressed as linear inequalities.\"\"\",1\n1706,\"\"\"DISHWASHER (PRODUCT D)\"\"\",\"\"\"Product D is another product manufactured by the Large Appliances division, earning a contribution of $200 per unit.\"\"\",1\n1705,\"\"\"FREEZER (PRODUCT F)\"\"\",\"\"\"Product F is a product manufactured by the Large Appliances division, earning a contribution of $150 per unit.\"\"\",1\n2137,\"\"\"GRAPHICAL SOLUTION\"\"\",\"\"\"Graphical solution involves plotting the constraints on a 2D line chart to determine the optimal production plan. The optimal point is the intersection of the lines: a = 1,000 and materials constraint 3a + 4b = 30,000.\"\"\",2\n2135,\"\"\"LINEAR PROGRAMMING FOR OPTIMAL PRODUCTION PLAN WITH RESOURCE CONSTRAINTS\"\"\",\"\"\"A company uses linear programming to establish an optimal production plan to maximize profit, considering constraints on materials and labor. The company must meet a minimum order requirement for one of its products while optimizing the use of limited resources.\"\"\",2\n1710,\"\"\"SHADOW PRICE OF MATERIAL IN THE LARGE APPLIANCES DIVISION\"\"\",\"\"\"The shadow price of material in the Large Appliances division is $0, as material is not a binding constraint.\"\"\",1\n2136,\"\"\"CONSTRAINT EQUATIONS\"\"\",\"\"\"Constraint equations in linear programming are mathematical expressions that represent the limitations or requirements of the problem. In this case, the constraints include the availability of materials and labor, as well as the minimum order requirement for product A.\"\"\",1\n2138,\"\"\"OPTIMAL PRODUCTION PLAN\"\"\",\"\"\"The optimal production plan is to make 1,000 units of A and 6,750 units of B.\"\"\",1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n545,\"\"\"LINEAR PROGRAMMING\"\"\",\"\"\"CONSTRAINTS\"\"\",\"\"\"Linear programming involves expressing constraints as linear equations to define the limitations on decision variables.\"\"\",17\n549,\"\"\"LINEAR PROGRAMMING\"\"\",\"\"\"OBJECTIVE FUNCTION METHOD\"\"\",\"\"\"The objective function method is used in linear programming to evaluate the objective function at each vertex of the feasible region to determine the optimal solution.\"\"\",17\n569,\"\"\"FEASIBLE REGION\"\"\",\"\"\"LINEAR PROGRAMMING MODEL FOR CUT AND STITCH\"\"\",\"\"\"The Linear programming model for Cut and Stitch includes identifying the Feasible region on a graph where all constraints intersect.\"\"\",16\n550,\"\"\"LINEAR PROGRAMMING\"\"\",\"\"\"PRODUCTION CONSTRAINTS FOR PRODUCT F AND D\"\"\",\"\"\"Linear programming is used to determine the optimum production plan for Product F and D.\"\"\",16\n546,\"\"\"LINEAR PROGRAMMING\"\"\",\"\"\"GRAPHING A LINEAR PROGRAMMING MODEL\"\"\",\"\"\"Graphing a linear programming model is a feature of the linear programming methodology, involving steps to plot constraints and identify the feasible region.\"\"\",15\n544,\"\"\"LINEAR PROGRAMMING\"\"\",\"\"\"OBJECTIVE FUNCTION\"\"\",\"\"\"Linear programming involves formulating an objective function to either maximize contribution or minimize cost.\"\"\",15